Sure, here is a short presentation of a patient with rheumatoid arthritis:

Patient Demographics:

- Age: 48 years old
- Gender: Female
- Occupation: Office manager
- Medical history: Hypothyroidism, hypertension

Chief Complaint:

- Stiffness and swelling in the joints of the fingers, wrists, and ankles
- Pain and tenderness in the affected joints
- Difficulty with daily activities such as gripping objects, opening jars, and walking

Medical Assessment:

- Physical examination reveals swelling, warmth, and tenderness in the affected joints
- Lab tests show elevated levels of C-reactive protein (CRP) and erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR)
- X-rays show erosion and joint space narrowing in the wrists and hands

Diagnosis:

- Rheumatoid arthritis (RA)

Treatment:

- Patient is started on a disease-modifying anti-rheumatic drug (DMARD) to slow the progression of the disease
- Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) are prescribed to manage pain and inflammation
- Patient is referred to a physical therapist for exercises to improve joint mobility and strength
- Patient is advised to maintain a healthy lifestyle, including regular exercise and a balanced diet

Patient: Mrs. J, a 56-year-old female

Chief Complaint: Joint pain and stiffness

History of Present Illness: Mrs. J reports experiencing joint pain and stiffness for several months, particularly in her hands and feet. She has also noticed difficulty with grip strength and has developed some nodules on her fingers. The pain and stiffness are worse in the morning and improve throughout the day, but she still experiences some discomfort in the evening. She denies any other significant symptoms.

Past Medical History: Mrs. J has a history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and osteoporosis for which she takes medication.

Social History: She is married and lives with her husband. She is retired and enjoys spending time with her grandchildren.

Physical Exam: On exam, Mrs. J has swelling and tenderness in multiple joints, including the metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints, as well as the ankles and knees. She has limited range of motion in these joints. There are nodules palpable on her fingers. No other significant findings are noted.

Assessment: Based on her symptoms and physical exam, Mrs. J is diagnosed with rheumatoid arthritis.
